<taxonomicName id="3CB44D32FA2DFFD06D21F8366A80F834" authorityName="Boursin" authorityYear="1964" box="[1086,1212,1952,1976]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="596" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2DFFD06D21F8366A80F834" box="[1086,1212,1952,1976]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="596">Blepharosis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The new species is best distinguished by the unicolorous brown body and forewing in which only the ochre or pale brown orbicular and
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FB0B36B1FA2CFFD16988FF0E6D61FED0" blockId="1.[151,1436,152,487]" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
reniform stigmata are conspicuous, while the rest of the wing pattern remains conjectural. It is very different externally from 
<taxonomicName id="3CB44D32FA2CFFD169CDFF2C6FAEFF5D" baseAuthorityName="Alpheraky" baseAuthorityYear="1892" box="[210,402,185,209]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="597" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anachoretoides">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2CFFD169CDFF2C6FAEFF5D" box="[210,402,185,209]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">B. anachoretoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="638F2A34FA2CFFD168BEFF2C6C3CFF5D" box="[417,512,186,209]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1897,1919]" captionTargetBox="[165,1430,541,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[165,1430,541,1866]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Blepharosis spp. male adults. 1. B. sirotka sp. n., holotype, China, Sichuan, PGY4893m (PGM/HNHM); 2. B. sirotka sp. n., Paratype, China, Sichuan (ASV); 3. B. sirotka sp. n., Paratype, China, Sichuan (AFM); 4. B. sirotka sp. n., Paratype, China, Sichuan (AFM); 5. B. anachoretoides, China, Qinghai (PGM); 6. B. anachoretoides, China, Qinghai PGY4911m (PGM)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3715700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3715700/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">Figs 5, 6</figureCitation>
) (the only close congener regarding their male genital structures) which has narrower, more variegated forewing; whitish to pale yellow reniform stigma, of which the continuation along the lower cellvein reaches the base of wing; brown coloration restricted to the middle, while the outer part of the basal and the inner half of the marginal areas are suffused with whitish-grey well-defined antemedial, postmedial and subterminal crosslines and whitish-grey covered veins; and much lighter hindwing inner area.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FB0B36B1FA2CFFD169D8FEFE6A33FE6B" blockId="1.[151,1436,152,487]" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">
In the male genitalia features, 
<taxonomicName id="3CB44D32FA2CFFD16B0FFEFE6C44FEF3" authorityName="Gyulai &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Truuverk &amp; Vaitonis" authorityYear="2019" box="[528,632,359,383]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="597" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sirotka">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2CFFD16B0FFEFE6C44FEF3" box="[528,632,359,383]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">B. sirotka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="638F2A34FA2CFFD16B97FEFE6CD4FEF3" box="[648,744,360,383]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1764,1786]" captionTargetBox="[162,1436,195,1733]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,191,1743]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Blepharosis spp. male genitalia. 7. B. sirotka sp. n., holotype, China, Sichuan, PGY4893m (PGM/HNHM); 8. B. sirotka sp. n., paratype, China, Sichuan, PGY4924m (ASV); 9. B. anachoretoides, China, Qinghai, PGY4911m (PGM);" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3715702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3715702/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">Figs 7, 8</figureCitation>
