<figureCitation id="638F2A34FA2CFFD16D4BFEFE6AAAFEF3" box="[1108,1174,360,383]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1764,1786]" captionTargetBox="[162,1436,195,1733]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,191,1743]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Blepharosis spp. male genitalia. 7. B. sirotka sp. n., holotype, China, Sichuan, PGY4893m (PGM/HNHM); 8. B. sirotka sp. n., paratype, China, Sichuan, PGY4924m (ASV); 9. B. anachoretoides, China, Qinghai, PGY4911m (PGM);" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3715702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3715702/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="597">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) by the apically smaller horned uncus; terminally prominent cucullus, stronger, in the basal section much broader, slightly longer digitus which is partly fused with the continuation of the ampullar plate and the somewhat shorter aedeagus with smooth ventral carinal plate and with slightly more ample vesica armed with basally thicker distal cornuti.
