<paragraph id="FB0B36B1FA2FFFD269D8F8D46CDAF868" blockId="2.[151,1436,1858,2020]" pageId="2" pageNumber="598">
The entire structure of the male genitalia (shape of uncus, valvae, juxta, the lack of the clasper and ampulla and the vesica configuration) of the new species is, however, so strongly similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="3CB44D32FA2FFFD26D2DF8F36ACAF8F0" baseAuthorityName="Alpheraky" baseAuthorityYear="1892" box="[1074,1270,1892,1916]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anachoretoides">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2FFFD26D2DF8F36ACAF8F0" box="[1074,1270,1892,1916]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="598">B. anachoretoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that it became necessary to compare their DNA to decide their taxonomic relationship. The separation of the two taxa as two distinct species is further supported by their different habitats and the unusually late flight period of the new species compared to 
<taxonomicName id="3CB44D32FA2FFFD26988F85B6F6BF868" baseAuthorityName="Alpheraky" baseAuthorityYear="1892" box="[151,343,1996,2020]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="598" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anachoretoides">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2FFFD26988F85B6F6BF868" box="[151,343,1996,2020]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="598">B. anachoretoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which is a typically summer species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B3AE653AFA2EFFD369D8FF0E6EC6FC25" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" type="description">
<paragraph id="FB0B36B1FA2EFFD369D8FF0E6D23FED0" blockId="3.[151,1436,152,1111]" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2EFFD369D8FF0E6F77FF23" bold="true" box="[199,331,152,175]" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">Description</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="638F2A34FA2EFFD3687FFF0E6FF4FF23" box="[352,456,152,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–6" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1897,1919]" captionTargetBox="[165,1430,541,1866]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[165,1430,541,1866]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–6. Blepharosis spp. male adults. 1. B. sirotka sp. n., holotype, China, Sichuan, PGY4893m (PGM/HNHM); 2. B. sirotka sp. n., Paratype, China, Sichuan (ASV); 3. B. sirotka sp. n., Paratype, China, Sichuan (AFM); 4. B. sirotka sp. n., Paratype, China, Sichuan (AFM); 5. B. anachoretoides, China, Qinghai (PGM); 6. B. anachoretoides, China, Qinghai PGY4911m (PGM)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3715700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3715700/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">Figs 1–4</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 
<quantity id="3C4C9B54FA2EFFD36B44FF0E6CD6FF23" box="[603,746,152,175]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.375" metricValueMax="2.45" metricValueMin="2.3" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" unit="mm" value="23.75" valueMax="24.5" valueMin="23.0">23–24,5 mm</quantity>
(
<typeStatus id="240F8813FA2EFFD36BE1FF0E6D61FF23" box="[766,861,152,175]" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">holotype</typeStatus>
<quantity id="3C4C9B54FA2EFFD36A74FF0E6DE8FF23" box="[875,980,152,175]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.45" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" unit="mm" value="24.5">24,5 mm</quantity>
), length of forewing 
<quantity id="3C4C9B54FA2EFFD36DCEFF0E6B5DFF23" box="[1233,1377,152,175]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.175" metricValueMax="1.25" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" unit="mm" value="11.75" valueMax="12.5" valueMin="11.0">11–12,5 mm</quantity>
. The remarkable external features of the new species are the finely serrate male antennae; the gracile body with brown vestiture; the pointed forewing apex; the pale brown to reddish-brown ground colour of forewings; the general absence of wing pattern excepting pale ochreous reniform and orbicular stigmata, the latter of which is flattened-elongate and usually confluent with the reniform stigma; the only slightly lighter inner area of the hindwing; and the patternless underside with its colouration being similar to the upperside.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FB0B36B1FA2EFFD369D8FEFE6F55FD18" blockId="3.[151,1436,152,1111]" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="638F2A34FA2EFFD36872FEFE6FF7FEF3" box="[365,459,360,383]" captionStart="FIGURES 7–9" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1764,1786]" captionTargetBox="[162,1436,195,1733]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,191,1743]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 7–9. Blepharosis spp. male genitalia. 7. B. sirotka sp. n., holotype, China, Sichuan, PGY4893m (PGM/HNHM); 8. B. sirotka sp. n., paratype, China, Sichuan, PGY4924m (ASV); 9. B. anachoretoides, China, Qinghai, PGY4911m (PGM);" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3715702" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3715702/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">Figs 7, 8</figureCitation>
). The most conspicuous features are the long, distally curved, terminally finely hooked, thin uncus based on short tegumen; the densely hairy, rounded penicular lobes; the broadly pentagonal, weakly sclerotised juxta, apically with medial depression; the U-shaped vinculum; the nearly symmetrical, broad and straight valvae, the densely hairy, terminally somewhat prominent, rounded cucullus without corona; the conspicuous, slightly curved, basally broader, apically pointed, strongly sclerotized digitus which is partly fused with the continuation of the ampullar plate; the long, narrow, strongly sclerotized bar-like basal plate of the harpe (clasper); the rather straight, cylindrical aedeagus with smooth carina; and the short, evenly ample, membranous, dorsally everted vesica, bearing three broadbased, short and acute thorns, of which the distal two are obliquely wedge-shaped, the basal one is drawing-pin-like. The female is unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FB0B36B1FA2EFFD369D8FD366F92FD55" blockId="3.[151,1436,152,1111]" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2EFFD369D8FD366F9CFD3B" bold="true" box="[199,416,672,695]" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">Molecular analysis</emphasis>
. Three identical DNA barcodes of 
<taxonomicName id="3CB44D32FA2EFFD36A31FD366DA5FD3B" authorityName="Gyulai &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Truuverk &amp; Vaitonis" authorityYear="2019" box="[814,921,671,695]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sirotka">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2EFFD36A31FD366DA5FD3B" box="[814,921,671,695]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">B. sirotka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differed from a single 658 bp sequence of 
<taxonomicName id="3CB44D32FA2EFFD36C9AFD366F06FD55" baseAuthorityName="Alpheraky" baseAuthorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anachoretoides">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2EFFD36C9AFD366F06FD55" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">B. anachoretoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 13.5%.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FB0B36B1FA2EFFD369D8FD736EC6FC25" blockId="3.[151,1436,152,1111]" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">
By the information of Reza Zahiri (pers. comm.), 
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2EFFD36BC9FD726DA7FD70" box="[726,923,740,764]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">Amphipoea fucosa</emphasis>
to be the nearest or the most similar sequence to 
<taxonomicName id="3CB44D32FA2EFFD36988FC9E6EC3FC93" authorityName="Gyulai &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Truuverk &amp; Vaitonis" authorityYear="2019" box="[151,255,775,799]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sirotka">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2EFFD36988FC9E6EC3FC93" box="[151,255,775,799]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">B. sirotka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(~5%), based on his own research. Our decision on the genus selection based on the very similar external and particularly the male genitalia features of the 
<taxonomicName id="3CB44D32FA2EFFD36B85FCBF6DFAFCCD" baseAuthorityName="Alpheraky" baseAuthorityYear="1892" box="[666,966,809,833]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anachoretoides">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2EFFD36B85FCBF6DFAFCCD" box="[666,966,809,833]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">Blepharosis anachoretoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This idea concerning 
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2EFFD36DD4FCBF6B78FCCD" box="[1227,1348,809,833]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">Amphipoea</emphasis>
is very interesting and useful, however 
<taxonomicName id="3CB44D32FA2EFFD368E3FCDB6C5BFCE8" authorityName="Gyulai &amp; Saldaitis &amp; Truuverk &amp; Vaitonis" authorityYear="2019" box="[508,615,844,868]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Blepharosis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sirotka">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2EFFD368E3FCDB6C5BFCE8" box="[508,615,844,868]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">B. sirotka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cannot be an 
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2EFFD36A13FCDA6DB9FCE8" box="[780,901,844,868]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">Amphipoea</emphasis>
, since those are very distinctive in the external features, having well detached cucullus with corona and very different shape of vesica and configuration, etc. in the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B3AE653AFA2EFFD369D8FC236A88FB9D" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="FB0B36B1FA2EFFD369D8FC236A88FB9D" blockId="3.[151,1436,152,1111]" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2EFFD369D8FC236FE7FC40" bold="true" box="[199,475,949,972]" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">Biology and distribution</emphasis>
. Six males were collected at light on 
<date id="8F0A1071FA2EFFD36A79FC236DDCFC40" box="[870,992,949,972]" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" value="2017-09-21">
21.IX. 
<quantity id="3C4C9B54FA2EFFD36AB9FC236DDCFC40" box="[934,992,949,972]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.12318" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" unit="in" value="2017.0">2017</quantity>
</date>
in a remote part of 
<collectingRegion id="3970F853FA2EFFD36DB1FC236B5BFC40" box="[1198,1383,949,972]" country="China" name="Sichuan" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">Sichuan province</collectingRegion>
near the Litang of the Shaluli Shan mountain range, in 
<collectingCountry id="83A37621FA2EFFD36BAFFC4E6CCFFC63" box="[688,755,984,1007]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">China</collectingCountry>
. The new species was collected during a single cold night in an alpine grassland (at ca 
<quantity id="3C4C9B54FA2EFFD36894FC6C6FE0FB9D" box="[395,476,1018,1041]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.2" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" unit="m" value="4200.0">4200 m</quantity>
altitude) where the vegetation was damaged by people and animals.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B3AE653AFA2EFFD369D8FB8B6F83FBDB" pageId="3" pageNumber="599" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="FB0B36B1FA2EFFD369D8FB8B6F83FBDB" blockId="3.[151,1436,152,1111]" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">
<emphasis id="C9C0EAA3FA2EFFD369D8FB8B6F7BFBB8" bold="true" box="[199,327,1053,1076]" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species name “sirotka” in Russian refers to the desolate and hostile 
<typeStatus id="240F8813FA2EFFD36DBBFB8B6AEEFBB8" box="[1188,1234,1053,1076]" pageId="3" pageNumber="599">type</typeStatus>
locality with very depauperate moth diversity.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
